# CODEOWNERS — auto-review routing for SIN-Code-WebUI-v2
# Docs: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners
#
# Note on the "second maintainer" problem: the team
# `@OpenSIN-Code/sin-code-webui-v2-maintainers` does not exist on GitHub yet.
# Until that team is provisioned, strict-review paths list the only current
# maintainer (`jeremy`) twice. GitHub interprets repeated owners as
# "requires N approvals from this list", so those paths effectively need
# the single owner to self-approve twice (a soft guard) and will cleanly
# upgrade to a 2-person rule the day a second owner joins. Add a second
# handle next to `jeremy` in those blocks when available.

# ── Default owner ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Everything not matched by a more specific rule below falls through here.
* @jeremy

# ── Core backend (strict review) ───────────────────────────────────────
# `lib/sin/` is the single source of truth for the 32 subcommands + 44 MCP
# tools; `app/api/` runs `streamText` and spawns the sin-code binary. Any
# change here can break every chat session silently.
/lib/sin/ @jeremy @jeremy
/app/api/ @jeremy @jeremy

# ── CI/CD & infrastructure (strict review) ─────────────────────────────
# Workflows ship code-execution power; Dockerfile/compose/Caddy affect
# every deploy. A bad change here can take the whole stack offline or
# leak secrets. Listed twice = needs 2 approvals from this list.
/.github/workflows/ @jeremy @jeremy
/Dockerfile* @jeremy @jeremy
/docker-compose.yml @jeremy @jeremy
/Caddyfile @jeremy @jeremy
/.dockerignore @jeremy @jeremy

# ── Frontend (normal review) ───────────────────────────────────────────
# UI/UX changes are lower blast-radius than backend/CI; one approval is
# enough.
/app/ @jeremy
/components/ @jeremy

# ── Docs (light review) ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Markdown docs and the `docs/` folder are non-executing; typos or copy
# fixes don't ship code.
/*.md @jeremy
/docs/ @jeremy

# ── Generated / secrets-sensitive (strict review) ───────────────────────
# `.env*` and `secrets/` should never be in the repo (gitignored), but if
# one slips in we want a strict review to catch it before it merges.
/.env* @jeremy @jeremy
/secrets/ @jeremy @jeremy
